{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17618230","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17618230"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":1,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T15:20:40+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T15:20:40+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16501"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"16501","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/16501"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"9192"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"75280"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"9192","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/9192"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16501"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"60788"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"4930"},{"type":"tags","id":"4931"},{"type":"tags","id":"4941"},{"type":"tags","id":"4942"},{"type":"tags","id":"7659"},{"type":"tags","id":"8569"},{"type":"tags","id":"10320"},{"type":"tags","id":"10374"},{"type":"tags","id":"10473"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"21805"},{"type":"contributions","id":"21809"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"75280","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/75280"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EGolgi tendon organs are specialized mechanoreceptors located at the junction between skeletal muscle fibers and tendons. They monitor muscle tension during both passive stretch and active contraction.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following best describes the primary sensory neurons that innervate Golgi tendon organs?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Type Ia (A alpha) afferents","Type Ib (A alpha) afferents","Type II (A beta) afferents","Type III (A delta) afferents","Type IV (C) afferents"],"correctOptions":[1],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EType Ib (A alpha) afferents\u003C/strong\u003E are the primary sensory neurons that innervate Golgi tendon organs. These large, myelinated fibers conduct rapidly and are specialized for detecting changes in muscle tension.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe other types of sensory neurons serve different functions:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EType Ia (A alpha) afferents\u003C/strong\u003E innervate muscle spindles and detect muscle length and rate of stretch\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EType II (A beta) afferents\u003C/strong\u003E innervate various cutaneous mechanoreceptors and detect touch and pressure\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EType III (A delta) afferents\u003C/strong\u003E conduct fast pain and temperature sensations\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EType IV (C) afferents\u003C/strong\u003E are unmyelinated and conduct slow pain, temperature, and crude touch\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003EGolgi tendon organs work with muscle spindles to provide proprioceptive feedback about muscle tension and length, contributing to motor control and posture.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe type of afferent (i.e. I-IV or A to C) reflects its size, myelination and thus speed of transmission. The A alpha or Group I afferent axons transmit their signals the fastest, being the largest in diameter with the most myelination. Group IV or C afferents are unmyelinated and the slowest. \u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Golgi tendon organs are innervated by type Ib (A alpha) afferent neurons which detect muscle tension.","Different types of sensory neurons have distinct roles: Ia for muscle spindles, Ib for tendon organs, II for touch, III for temperature/fast pain, and IV for slow pain.","Sensory neurons can be classed based on their size and degree of myelination, which reflects their conduction speed."],"references":["Oliver KM, Florez-Paz DM, Badea TC, Mentis GZ, Menon V, de Nooij JC. Molecular correlates of muscle spindle and Golgi tendon organ afferents(link is external and opens in a new window). Nat Commun. 2021 Mar 1;12(1):1451.","Hall, J. E., \u0026 Hall, M. E. (2020). Guyton and Hall Textbook of Medical Physiology E-Book: Guyton and Hall Textbook of Medical Physiology E-Book. Elsevier Health Sciences.","Singh, V. (2024).\u00a0Textbook of Clinical Neuroanatomy-E-Book. Elsevier Health Sciences."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"60788"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16501"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"60788","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/60788"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-12-29T16:09:53+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-12-29T16:10:26+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"9192"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"75280"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"67","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/67"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Basic Science","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"71","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/71"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Junior","synonyms":null,"description":"Suitable for a junior, pre-clinical medical student","position":0,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","